statement.p:
Given any two sequences u and w,
if u_0=w_0 and \nabla u_n = \nabla w_n for all n \gt 0,
then u_n = w_n for all n \ge 0.

We say that u is increasing (order preserving) on the index range m,\ldots,n 
if for every index values i and j with m \le i \lt j \le n, 
we have u_i \lt u_j.

We say that u is decreasing (order reversing) on the index range m,\ldots,n 
if for every index values i and j with m \le i \lt j \le n, 
we have u_i \gt u_j.

solution.p:
Because u is an accumulation of x, we can determine where u is increasing or decreasing based on the signs of the increments x. We solve the inequality x_k \gt 0 using the explicit formula for x_k.
2k-13 \gt 0 2k \gt 13 k \gt \frac{13}{2}
The smallest integer greater than \frac{13}{2} is k=7. We see that x_k \gt 0 for any k \ge 7. By the same steps, we see that x_k \lt 0 for any k \le 6.

